abstract = {In structural health monitoring, distributed sensing offers a unique competitive advantage against discrete sensing in its improved spatial resolution and increased damage detectability. Improved spatial resolution is achieved by the developments in fiber-optical sensors. Increased damage detectability is enabled via spatial correlation among measurements. In this chapter, the principle of distributed surface sensing for structural health monitoring is first introduced. Mechanical analysis of beam and pipeline structures using distributed surface sensing for damage detection and health monitoring is provided, followed by experimental results of distributed surface sensing on laboratory beam and pipeline specimens. Finally, research findings and future recommendations in the design and application of distributed surface sensing for civil infrastructure systems are summarized.}
}
